The "Why": What is the fundamental difference between WHERE and HAVING? Can they be used in the same query? 
WHERE: Filters individual rows before any grouping or calculations occur. It cannot see aggregate data (like SUM or AVG).
HAVING: Filters grouped data after the GROUP BY clause has been processed. It is specifically designed to work with aggregate functions.

Scenario: Can you use HAVING without a GROUP BY clause?
Answer: Yes, but it treats the entire table as a single group. For example, SELECT SUM(salary) FROM Employees HAVING SUM(salary) > 1000000; will return the sum only if the total company payroll exceeds a million.
